observations.recommendation:
a. The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality and render a Report on the Physical Count of the Road Networks System;

b. The Municipal General Service Officer – Designate to: Render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map; Regularly maintains and updates the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads; Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;

c. The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Service Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

d. The Municipal Accountant to: Prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card; Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; Disclose in the Notes to FS the length covered by the system, additions and reductions, major repairs and regular maintenance for the year.

We recommended that the Management:
Require the persons liable to immediately settle their outstanding balances, be it submission of liquidation reports or payroll deductions or withholding of salaries;
Require all Accountable Officers to adhere to the provisions of COA 97-002 on the prescribed period to liquidate cash advances;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide adjusting journal entries on the erroneous classification of advances for confidential funds; and
For dormant receivables, refer to Items 6.0 to 8.0 of COA Circular No. 2023-008 for the proper disposition and request for write-off.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to provide adjusting entries to properly reclassify the work animals as breeding stocks;
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to work hand in hand with the Municipal Agriculturist in establishing the correct balance of breeding stocks through the conduct of a physical count of animals;
Corroboration of available files and records of the Municipal Agriculturist to update the GSO and Accounting records;
Require the responsible offices to recognize changes in fair value of the animals and if the fair market value could not be reasonably measured due to lack of appraisers, request assistance from the Department of Agriculture; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to provide adequate disclosures under the provisions of IPSAS 27 on the fair presentation of biological assets.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to review the transactions in question and provide adjusting journal entries to rectify the erroneous accounting entries made;
Looking forward, direct the Municipal Budget Officer to obligate lawful expenditures and obligations at year-end for it to be classified as an Accounts Payable;
Require the persons responsible to immediately submit the original copies of the delivery receipts on the abovementioned transactions; and
Enforce an unyielding commitment to adhere to best operation practices by submitting original file copies to the Auditor in compliance with Section 39 of PD 1445 and refrain from reusing duplicate attachments to other vouchers.

We recommended that the Management:
Avail of the one-time cleansing of dormant accounts by creating a task force to assist the Municipal Accountant in following the general guidelines and in preparing the required schedules for monitoring purposes as well as undertake the procedures for the proper disposition of dormant accounts as provided for under Items 6.0 and 7.0 of COA Circular 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Direct the Municipal Accountant through the HoA with/through the ATL and/or SA, depending on the jurisdictional amount, to file a request for the approval of COA to write off/derecognize from the books the dormant accounts in compliance with Item 8.0 of the Circular within one (I) year from the effectivity of the Circular. The request shall be supported with the documents listed in Annex 8, provided with index tabs, for easy reference;
Prepare the Schedules of Dormant Accounts (SDA) quarterly to be submitted to the ATL/SA on or before the 15th day of the ensuing month and disclose comparative information in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the dormant accounts pursuant to Item 10.0 of the Circular; and
Looking forward, ensure that receivables below ten years are properly monitored to ensure their prompt collection and accurate recording in the FS including the provision of an allowance for impairment on receivables with doubtful collectability.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to assign personnel to take charge of stamping paid vouchers and liquidation reports with additional information like the employee’s name, signature, and date stamped;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to attach a copy of the check disbursements journal along with the Report on Checks Issued when submitting the monthly DVs;
Direct the person responsible to properly state the purpose of cash advances when preparing the DV including its complete supporting documents to establish the necessity of the cash advance;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to post a PhilGEPS invitation to bid for projects with an ABC of ₱50,000.00 and above;
Strictly enforce the Inspection Officer's presence during the delivery of items. In her absence, ensure the presence of an inspectorate team representative to sign the IAR; and
Attach a copy of the documentary checklist in every DV as a guide on its proper supporting attachment. Also, direct all requesting personnel/departments to ensure that all details on the supporting documents are completely and thoroughly filled up.

a.	The GSO and Municipal Accounting Offices exert more efforts in keeping and maintaining the property records up to date and take note of the procedures in the conduct of inventory taking which includes cases when no information could be found in both accounting and property records as stated in Section 6 of the COA Circular whichever is applicable;

b. 	The Office of the Mayor assigns or designate additional personnel to aid the GSO and inventory committee to ensure the completion and submission of the annual physical count of properties; and

c. 	Looking forward, ensure that the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE as provided for in COA Circular 2020-006 are strictly observed to facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

a. The Office of the Mayor and the Municipal Accountant prioritize the assignment of a competent personnel in the Accounting Office who will be assigned to update the subsidiary ledgers of the cash accounts as well as focus on the preparation of bank reconciliation statements of the Municipality and its composite barangays with all of its supporting documents to aid in the verification of the report;

b. The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant prepare a timetable of activities including the responsible persons who will take charge of the possible plan of actions of the LGU with the end purpose of facilitating the prompt preparation and submission of the Bank Reconciliation Reports, which may include the enrollment to the bank’s online facilities and to fast track the updating of the subsidiary ledgers utilizing the SPIDC;

c. The Municipal Accountant inform the bank that the authorized recipient of the bank statements shall be the Municipal Accountant only for proper segregation of duties; and

d. The Municipal Accountant submit the Bank Reconciliation Statements to COA for verification in accordance with COA Circular No. 96-011 and conduct quarterly reconciliation of cash balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be adjusted and posted in their respective books.

a. The GSO – Designate procure office supplies based on the Approved Procurement Plan on a quarterly basis instead of procuring independently by office to avail of advantageous bulk purchase prices and also to avoid price fluctuations of purchasing the same supplies from different suppliers;

b. The Municipal Accountant apply the perpetual inventory method and the accounting standards of recording purchases of office supplies as inventories, recognize the corresponding issuances to the concerned offices and maintain supplies ledger cards; 

c. The GSO – Designate to complete the preparation and maintenance of stock cards and regularly reconcile with the supplies ledger cards of the Accounting Unit; monitor the issuance of supplies to each office by using the Requisition Issue Slip and reporting the same to the Accounting Department monthly using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued for the month together with the stock card as proof; and

d. The GSO – Designate in cooperation with other relevant offices to ensure compliance with the required conduct of physical inventory of supplies every semester to ensure accurate and fair presentation of the reported amounts in the financial statements at year-end.

